<subSubSection box="[140,630,1398,1425]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="49.[140,1108,1398,1672]" box="[140,630,1398,1425]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<heading box="[140,630,1398,1425]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[140,630,1398,1425]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
5. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1893" box="[168,332,1398,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Opostegidae</taxonomicName>
– white eye-cap moths
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="50" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="49.[140,1108,1398,1672]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
Minute (
<quantity box="[243,358,1434,1460]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" unit="mm" value="9.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="6.0">6–12 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with predominantly white wings. Th ey can be separated from most other small moths by the combination of a tuft of hairlike scales on the head, presence of an antennal eye cap, and primitive wing venation. They can be separated from the 
<taxonomicName box="[386,531,1539,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Nepticulidae</taxonomicName>
by the absence of extensive dark areas on the forewings. Larvae are leafminers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="49.[140,1108,1398,1672]" lastBlockId="50.[140,1108,167,299]" lastPageId="50" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
Over 100 species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1893" box="[422,563,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Opostegidae</taxonomicName>
are known worldwide, with many undescribed species expected to be found. Ten species are known from North America; one of these is known from AB. Taxonomic coverage of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1893" box="[673,814,167,193]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Opostegidae</taxonomicName>
is excellent: 
<bibRefCitation author="Davis DR" box="[958,1107,167,193]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="1 - 197" refId="ref240889" refString="Davis DR (1989) Generic revision of the Opostegidae, with a synoptic catalog of the world's species (Lepidoptera: Nepticuloidea). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology 478: 1 - 197." type="journal article" year="1989">Davis (1989)</bibRefCitation>
provided a genus-level treatment and catalog for the world 
<taxonomicName authority=", Diskus and Puplesis (2003)" authorityName=", Diskus and Puplesis" authorityYear="2003" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Acontiinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fauna">
fauna, 
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis R &amp; Diskus A" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" refId="ref263514" refString="Puplesis R, Diskus A (2003) Th e Nepticuloidea and Tischerioidea (Lepidoptera) - a global review, with strategic regional revisions. Lutule Publishers, Kaunas, Lithuania, 512 pp." type="book" year="2003">Diskus and Puplesis (2003)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
a catalog of the world fauna, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Davis DR &amp; Stonis JR" box="[602,877,237,263]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="1 - 212" refId="ref241007" refString="Davis DR, Stonis JR (2007) A revision of the New World plant-mining moths of the family Opostegidae (Lepidoptera: Nepticuloidea). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology 625: 1 - 212." type="journal article" year="2007">Davis and Stonis (2007)</bibRefCitation>
a monograph of the New World fauna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
